Hey Denzel! 

I believe there are many different ways newcomers could adapt to far warmer climates like Vegas! For example, I live in Florida, and here, rather than it getting cooler at night, OUR heat, remains pretty consistent (except in wintertime of course) and as such, I am always getting asked how we handle it, however, for vegas and california, it is a more unique situation. Their air is FAR Drier than anything we have here in florida, as such, the heat that is experienced during the daylight hours does not remain for long after the sun sets. In science heat tends to want to hold on to water which is also why hurricanes become so much stronger when warm water is present (i.e. the caribbean chain of islands). However, because this dry air is present, it offers a much better chance for tolerable conditions and also offers a much easier transition especially if the family is coming from a country or state that already had drier weather. Additionally, It's definitely helpful to keep a water bottle or sunshade umbrella handy during the day!
